ticipants.A labor history and an ethnography, Colonial Migrants evokes the violence, fieldwork, food, lodging, surveillance, and coercion that these workers experienced on farms and conveys their hopes and struggles to overcome poverty. Island farmworkers encountered a unique form of prejudice and racism arising from their dual status as both U.S. citizens and as "foreign others," and their experiences were further shaped by evolving immigration policies. Despite these challenges, many Puerto Rican farmworkers ultimately chose to settle in rural U.S. communities, contributing to the production of food and the Latinization of the U.S. farm labor force.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aMigrant laborzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aPuerto RicanszUnited StatesxMigrations. 0aPuerto RicanszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aamerican colonialism.  acivil rights.  acoercion.  acolonialism.  acommodification.  adebt slavery.  aethnic studies.  aethnography.  afarm labor program.  afarming.  afarms.  afields.  aforeign others.  ahispanic american studies.  ahispanic.  ahistory.  ahuman rights.  ahuman trafficking.  aimmigration.  alabor camps.  alabor industrial relations.  alabor.  alatino.  alatinx.  amigrant workers.  apolitical science.  aprejudice.  apuerto rico.  arace.  aracism.  arural communities.  aslave labor.  asurveillance.  aus territory.  aworkers rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part 